result.execSummary:
The defendant Jacqueline E. Ipsa was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.

The employment is stayed if the defendant is pursing her GED. 

The defendant must obtain her GED.

The defendant may not consume/possess any alcohol.

The defendant may not enter any bars/taverns.

The defendant must take all medications as prescribed.

The defendant must attend at least 1 AA/NA meeting per week.

The defendant must comply with all requirements in the CHIPS action.

The defendant must continue to follow thru with all current treatment plans.

The defendant must submit a DNA sample with the surcharge assessed.

timeConds.notes: Defendant must complete coummunity service within the first 6 months of probation.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Jacqueline E. Ipsa in court with attorney Mary L.R. Burns.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called 1:51 p.m. Burns hands court character references and court reviews. State - joint recommendation - enter a G plea, place on probation for 2 years, fine $300 plus costs, conditions AODA, maintain absolute sobriety, no possession of alcohol, no entry into bars/taverns, full time employment/schooling, 100 hours community service, take all medications as prescribed. All parties agree. Ipsa pleads G. Court goes over plea questionaire with defendant and finds that she if freely, voluntarily and intelligently waiving her right to a JT by entering her plea. Court accepts plea and adjudges guilty. State makes statement. Burns makes final statement. Ipsa with holds comment. Court receives letters submitted by defense. Court accepts joint recommendation and sentences defendant to the following: Count 1 - With hold sentence and place on probation for 2 years with conditions of - fine of $300 plus costs, DNA surcharge, follow all treatment plans already in place, no consumption or possession of alcohol, no entry into bars/taverns, take all medications as prescribed, full time employment with verbage, 100 HR community service within first 6 months of probation, required to complete GED, if pursuing GED no employment requirement, must attend one AA/NA meeting per week, comply with all requirements in CHIPS action. One day jail credit stipulated, if revoked. Appeal and voting rights given. Adjourned.

Defendant Jacqueline E. Ipsa in court with attorney Mary L.R. Burns.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called 3:44 pm. Waiver of preliminary hearing filed. Court finds waiver if voluntarily and intelligently, accepts waiver and accepts waiver. State has filed information (mirrors) - court finds probable cause, binds over for trial. Waive further reading and pleads NG to only count. Bond continued.  Final pre-trial scheduled for April 1, 2015 at 01:45 pm.
